SIMPLE: monad
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Monad
<hw>Mon"ad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>monas</ets>,
<ets>-adis</ets>, a unit, Gr. <?/, <?/, fr. <grk>mo`nos</grk>
alone.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An ultimate atom, or simple, unextended
point; something ultimate and indivisible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Philos. of Leibnitz)</fld> <def>The elementary and
indestructible units which were conceived of as endowed with the power
to produce all the changes they undergo, and thus determine all physical
and spiritual phenomena.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the smallest flagellate
Infusoria; esp., the species of the genus <gen>Monas</gen>, and allied
genera.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>A simple, minute organism; a
primary cell, germ, or plastid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An atom or radical whose valence
is one, or which can combine with, be replaced by, or exchanged for, one
atom of hydrogen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Monad deme</b></col> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, <cd>in
tectology, a unit of the first order of individuality.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 938 --></p>

<p><ent>Monadaria</ent>⟦br⟧
